# Code Quality

## Principles

- **SOLID**: Single Responsibility, Open/Closed, Liskov Substitution, Interface Segregation, Dependency Inversion
- **DRY**: Don't Repeat Yourself -- extract shared logic, but avoid premature abstraction
- **KISS**: Keep It Simple -- prefer clarity over cleverness
- **YAGNI**: You Aren't Gonna Need It -- do not build speculative features

## Readability

- Favor descriptive names over comments
- Functions should do one thing and be under 30 lines
- Classes should have a single responsibility
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Avoid boolean parameters; use enums or separate methods instead
- Limit method parameters to 3-4; use parameter objects for more

## Error Handling

- Catch specific exceptions, never bare `catch (Exception e)`
- Log with context (what failed, what inputs, what state)
- Fail fast on invalid inputs at boundaries
- Use custom exceptions for domain-specific errors
- Never swallow exceptions silently

## Performance Defaults

- Avoid premature optimization; profile first
- Use appropriate data structures (HashMap for lookup, ArrayList for iteration)
- Batch database operations; avoid N+1 queries
- Cache expensive computations only when measured as necessary
- Use pagination for large result sets

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

| Pattern | Problem | Alternative |
|---------|---------|-------------|
| God class | Too many responsibilities | Split by domain concern |
| Magic numbers | Unclear intent | Named constants |
| Deep inheritance | Fragile hierarchies | Composition over inheritance |
| Stringly-typed | No compile-time safety | Enums, value objects |
| Service locator | Hidden dependencies | Constructor injection |
| Temporal coupling | Methods must be called in order | Builder or state machine |
